From the Bridge a visitor who looked up stream would also get a view across part of the arable ground, the Western Fields of Cambridge lt is possible that in the thirteenth century some portion ol these Fields, that for instance nearest to the River, had been turned into pastore, but, before hedgerows had come into being, and the cornhelds basked in sunshine unbroken by rows of trees, it would be possible to see from the Great Bridge ’ a long stretch of open land with its strips belonging to different owners, and therefore cultivated with a considerable variety both of produce and of method.
